---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import DiagramCard from "../components/DiagramCard.astro";
---

<Layout title="The Paper | RLSTC Documentation" currentPage="/paper">
  <div class="page-content py-12 lg:py-20">
    <div class="reveal">
      <span class="badge badge-accent mb-4">VLDB Journal 2024</span>
      <h1 class="section-title text-3xl lg:text-4xl mb-3">
        Sub-trajectory Clustering with Deep Reinforcement Learning
      </h1>
      <p class="section-subtitle mb-4">
        Anqi Liang, Bin Yao, Bo Wang, Yinpei Liu, Zhida Chen, Jiong Xie, Feifei Li
      </p>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-8">
        The VLDB Journal (2024) 33:685–702 &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00778-023-00833-w" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover transition-colors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          doi:10.1007/s00778-023-00833-w
        </a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp; Shanghai Jiao Tong University &amp; Alibaba Group
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Abstract -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Abstract
      </h2>
      <div class="glass p-6 !rounded-lg leading-relaxed text-text-secondary">
        Sub-trajectory clustering is a fundamental problem in many trajectory applications. Existing approaches usually
        divide the clustering procedure into two phases: segmenting trajectories into sub-trajectories and then clustering
        these sub-trajectories. However, researchers need to develop complex human-crafted segmentation rules for
        specific applications, making the clustering results sensitive to the segmentation rules and lacking in generality.
        To solve this problem, we propose a novel algorithm using the clustering results to <em class="text-accent">guide</em> the segmentation,
        which is based on <strong class="text-text-primary">reinforcement learning (RL)</strong>. The novelty is that the segmentation and clustering components
        cooperate closely and improve each other continuously to yield better clustering results. We model the
        procedure of trajectory segmentation as a <strong class="text-text-primary">Markov decision process (MDP)</strong> and apply
        <strong class="text-text-primary">Deep-Q-Network (DQN)</strong> learning to train an RL model for the segmentation and achieve excellent clustering
        results. Experimental results on real datasets demonstrate the superior performance of the proposed RL-based
        approach over state-of-the-art methods.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Key Contributions -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Key Contributions
      </h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <div class="text-accent text-lg mb-2">🧠</div>
          <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">First RL-Based Framework</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">First RL-based solution for sub-trajectory clustering, modeling segmentation as an MDP with data-driven trajectory segmentation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <div class="text-teal text-lg mb-2">🎯</div>
          <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">Creative MDP Design</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">5-feature state (OD_s, OD_n, OD_b, L_b, L_f) with reward derived from clustering quality, achieving data-driven segmentation without hand-crafted rules.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <div class="text-amber text-lg mb-2">⚡</div>
          <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">Efficiency Optimizations</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">MDL-based preprocessing, trapezoid approximation for IED, and incremental O(1) computation reduce distance computation cost per point.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <div class="text-purple text-lg mb-2">📊</div>
          <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary mb-1">Superior Results</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Outperforms 8 baselines: 36% OD improvement on T-Drive, 39% on Geolife. 57% and 44% SSE improvements respectively.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Figure 1: Problem Motivation -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Problem Motivation
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Four dissimilar trajectories share a similar portion (the black box in Fig. 1). Clustering whole trajectories
        fails to discover this local similarity — sub-trajectory clustering enables finding common patterns among
        trajectory portions, critical for applications like hurricane forecasting, traffic analysis, and site selection.
      </p>
      <DiagramCard caption="Fig. 1 — Four dissimilar trajectories with a similar portion (the part in the black box)" accent="accent">
        <img src="/images/paper/page_2.png" alt="Fig. 1: Problem motivation — four trajectories with similar sub-portions" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
      </DiagramCard>
    </section>

    <!-- Framework Overview — Fig. 4 & 5 -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Framework Overview
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        The RLSTC framework consists of an offline DQN training phase and an online RLSTC algorithm with interacting 
        segmentation and clustering components. The segmentation is modeled as an MDP where the agent observes 
        clustering quality features and decides whether to cut at each trajectory point.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
        <DiagramCard caption="Fig. 4 — Overview of the RL-based Solution" accent="teal">
          <img src="/images/paper/page_6.png" alt="Fig. 4: RL-based solution overview showing offline training and online RLSTC algorithm" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
        </DiagramCard>
        <DiagramCard caption="Fig. 6 — DQN learning procedure with replay memory and dual networks" accent="amber">
          <img src="/images/paper/page_8.png" alt="Fig. 6: DQN learning illustration with main network, target network, replay memory" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
        </DiagramCard>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- State Definition -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> MDP State Design
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        The state combines clustering quality signals with trajectory geometry. The paper defines 5 features that 
        balance expressiveness with training efficiency:
      </p>
      <div class="glass p-5 mb-4">
        <div class="math-block text-center">
          <span class="text-text-primary font-mono text-sm">
            s<sub>t</sub> = (s<sub>t</sub>(OD<sub>s</sub>), s<sub>t</sub>(OD<sub>n</sub>), OD<sub>b</sub>, s<sub>t</sub>(L<sub>b</sub>), s<sub>t</sub>(L<sub>f</sub>))
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-3 mb-4">
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-accent mb-1">OD<sub>s</sub> — Segment OD</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Overall distance if we <em>do</em> segment at current point. Computed incrementally (Eq. 15).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-teal mb-1">OD<sub>n</sub> — No-Segment OD</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Overall distance if we <em>don't</em> segment. Equal to previous OD (Eq. 16).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-amber mb-1">OD<sub>b</sub> — Baseline OD</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Expert knowledge from TRACLUS segmentation (Eq. 18). Accelerates convergence.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-purple mb-1">L<sub>b</sub> — Backward Length</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Fraction of trajectory consumed by the current sub-trajectory: m₁ / |T|</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-coral mb-1">L<sub>f</sub> — Forward Length</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Fraction of trajectory remaining: m₂ / |T|. Prevents myopic segmentation decisions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Reward & Bellman -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Reward Function & Learning
      </h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-text-primary mb-2">Immediate Reward</h4>
          <div class="math-block my-3">
            <span class="text-text-primary font-mono text-sm">r<sub>t</sub> = s<sub>t</sub>(OD) − s<sub>t+1</sub>(OD)</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">
            Maximizing cumulative reward R = s₁(OD) − s<sub>|T|</sub>(OD) is equivalent to minimizing final OD.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-5 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-text-primary mb-2">Bellman Equation</h4>
          <div class="math-block my-3">
            <span class="text-text-primary font-mono text-sm">Q*(s,a) = E[r<sub>t</sub> + γ max<sub>a'</sub> Q*(s<sub>t+1</sub>,a') | s<sub>t</sub>,a<sub>t</sub>]</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">
            γ = 0.99. DQN approximates Q* with neural network parameters θ, trained via MSE loss with target network soft-updates (ω = 0.001).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Algorithms -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Algorithms
      </h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <DiagramCard caption="Algorithm 2 — DQN learning with ε-greedy, replay memory, and soft target updates" accent="accent">
          <img src="/images/paper/page_8.png" alt="Algorithm 2: DQN learning pseudocode" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
        </DiagramCard>
        <DiagramCard caption="Algorithm 3 — RLSTC: iterative segmentation + clustering until center convergence" accent="teal">
          <img src="/images/paper/page_9.png" alt="Algorithm 3: RLSTC algorithm with center computation" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
        </DiagramCard>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Experimental Results -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Experimental Results
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Evaluated on <strong class="text-text-primary">T-Drive</strong> (9,937 taxi trajectories, Beijing) and 
        <strong class="text-text-primary">Geolife</strong> (17,070 GPS trajectories, 182 users). Compared against 8 baselines:
        TRACLUS, S²T-Clustering, SubCLUS, Greedy, CLUSTMOSA, HyperCLUS, RTCLUS, and RLSTC w/o simplification.
      </p>

      <DiagramCard caption="Fig. 8 & 9 — Clustering quality (OD and SSE) across 4 distance metrics on T-Drive and Geolife" accent="coral">
        <img src="/images/paper/page_12.png" alt="Figures 8 and 9: OD and SSE comparison bar charts across distance metrics" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
      </DiagramCard>

      <div class="glass p-5 mt-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-text-primary mb-3">Key Findings</h4>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <p class="text-text-muted"><strong class="text-accent">OD Improvement</strong></p>
            <ul class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1 space-y-1 ml-4 list-disc">
              <li>T-Drive: <strong>36%</strong> average improvement over baselines</li>
              <li>Geolife: <strong>39%</strong> average improvement over baselines</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-text-muted"><strong class="text-teal">SSE Improvement</strong></p>
            <ul class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1 space-y-1 ml-4 list-disc">
              <li>T-Drive: <strong>57%</strong> average improvement</li>
              <li>Geolife: <strong>44%</strong> average improvement</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Segmentation Method Comparison -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Segmentation Method Comparison
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        RLSTC-S (the segmentation component alone) outperforms all baselines across AHC, DBSCAN, and k-means
        clustering methods with 4 distance metrics, demonstrating adaptability.
      </p>
      <DiagramCard caption="Fig. 12 — Performance of different segmentation methods across AHC, DBSCAN, and k-means" accent="purple">
        <img src="/images/paper/page_14.png" alt="Fig. 12: Segmentation method comparison across clustering algorithms" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
      </DiagramCard>
    </section>

    <!-- Parameter Studies -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Parameter Studies
      </h2>
      <DiagramCard caption="Figs. 13-16 — Impact of OD_b, training data size, iterations, and Geolife visualization" accent="amber">
        <img src="/images/paper/page_15.png" alt="Parameter study results: OD_b ablation, training size trade-off, iteration convergence, and visualization" class="w-full rounded-lg" />
      </DiagramCard>

      <div class="glass p-5 mt-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-text-primary mb-3">Paper Tables — k-Value Sensitivity</h4>
        <table class="styled-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>k</th><th>5</th><th>8</th><th>10</th><th>12</th><th>14</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="font-semibold text-text-primary">T-Drive OD</td><td>0.49</td><td>0.46</td><td class="text-accent font-semibold">0.21</td><td>0.44</td><td>0.42</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="font-semibold text-text-primary">Geolife OD</td><td>0.052</td><td>0.051</td><td class="text-accent font-semibold">0.023</td><td>0.051</td><td>0.04</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-2">Table 2 — k = 10 achieves the best clustering quality on both datasets.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="glass p-5 mt-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-text-primary mb-3">Pretrained Model Portability (k = 10)</h4>
        <table class="styled-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Test k</th><th>5</th><th>8</th><th>10</th><th>12</th><th>15</th><th>20</th><th>40</th><th>60</th><th>80</th><th>100</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="font-semibold text-text-primary">T-Drive</td><td>0.25</td><td>0.22</td><td class="text-accent font-semibold">0.21</td><td>0.26</td><td>0.26</td><td class="text-coral">0.51</td><td class="text-coral">0.59</td><td class="text-coral">0.61</td><td class="text-coral">0.60</td><td class="text-coral">0.62</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="font-semibold text-text-primary">Geolife</td><td>0.04</td><td>0.04</td><td class="text-accent font-semibold">0.02</td><td>0.03</td><td>0.04</td><td class="text-coral">0.08</td><td class="text-coral">0.09</td><td class="text-coral">0.10</td><td class="text-coral">0.09</td><td class="text-coral">0.12</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-2">Table 3 — When test k differs from training k by &gt;50%, performance degrades substantially.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Hyperparameters -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Hyperparameter Summary
      </h2>
      <div class="glass p-5">
        <table class="styled-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Network</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">5 → 64 → 2</td><td>Two-layer feedforward with ReLU</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning Rate</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">0.001</td><td>SGD optimizer</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ε (exploration)</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">1.0 → 0.99ε (min 0.1)</td><td>Decays per step</td></tr>
            <tr><td>γ (discount)</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">0.99</td><td>High future-reward weight</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Replay memory</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">5,000</td><td>Fixed-size FIFO buffer</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Batch size</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">32</td><td>Per gradient step</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Target update ω</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">0.001</td><td>Soft update: θ' = ωθ + (1−ω)θ'</td></tr>
            <tr><td>k (clusters)</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">10</td><td>Default; tested 5, 8, 10, 12, 14</td></tr>
            <tr><td>τ (convergence)</td><td class="font-mono text-xs">0.1</td><td>Max center drift threshold</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Baselines -->
    <section class="mb-16 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Baselines Compared
      </h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-accent mb-1">TRACLUS (Lee et al., 2007)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">MDL segmentation + DBSCAN clustering. Classical partition-and-group framework.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-teal mb-1">S²T-Clustering (Pelekis et al., 2017)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Global voting with local density for segmentation and clustering.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-amber mb-1">SubCLUS (Agarwal et al., 2018)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Models problem as set-cover. Approximation solution. Fréchet distance only.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-purple mb-1">Greedy Method</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Degraded RLSTC: segments iff OD_s &lt; OD_n. Local optima trap.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-coral mb-1">CLUSTMOSA (Dutta et al., 2022)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Multi-objective simulated annealing with bearing-based segmentation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary mb-1">HyperCLUS (Xia et al.)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Segments into hypercubes. Fast but imprecise trajectory representation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary mb-1">RTCLUS (Qiao et al., 2022)</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Uses MBRs + R-tree index. Fast clustering but approximate distances.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="glass p-4 !rounded-lg">
          <h4 class="text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary mb-1">RLSTC w/o simplification</h4>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Ablation: same RL segmentation but skips MDL preprocessing. Slower but similar OD.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Time Complexity -->
    <section class="mb-12 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Time Complexity
      </h2>
      <div class="glass p-5">
        <div class="math-block text-center mb-4">
          <span class="text-text-primary font-mono">Total = O(c · (nN + mM + m'))</span>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-xs text-text-muted">
          <div>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Per-point cost: O(1)</strong><br/>
            State, action, cluster assignment, and update — all incremental.
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Per-iteration: O(nN)</strong><br/>
            n = avg trajectory length, N = total trajectories. Dominates mM and m' terms.
          </div>
          <div>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Total: ≈ O(nN)</strong><br/>
            c iterations converge quickly (typically &lt; 10). Overall approximated as O(nN).
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Full Paper Pages Gallery -->
    <section class="mb-12 reveal">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-display font-bold text-text-primary mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="text-accent">§</span> Full Paper Pages
      </h2>
      <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 text-sm">
        The complete 18-page paper from The VLDB Journal (2024), pages 685–702. Click any page to enlarge.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-3">
        {Array.from({ length: 18 }, (_, i) => i + 1).map((num) => (
          <a href={`/images/paper/page_${num}.png`} target="_blank" rel="noopener"
             class="glass p-2 !rounded-lg hover:border-accent/30 transition-all group">
            <img src={`/images/paper/page_${num}.png`} alt={`Paper page ${num}`}
                 class="w-full rounded opacity-90 group-hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-center text-[0.65rem] text-text-muted mt-1">Page {num}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="flex justify-between items-center pt-8 border-t border-white/[0.06] reveal">
      <a href="/experiments" class="text-text-muted hover:text-text-primary text-sm transition-colors">← Experiments</a>
      <a href="/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover text-sm font-semibold transition-colors">Back to Overview →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
